<!-- ─── SECTION 1: CONTEXT & SCOPE ─── -->
<section id="s1">
  <div class="section-header">
    <span class="section-num">01 //</span>
    <h2 class="section-title">Context &amp; <span class="highlight">Scope of Applicability</span></h2>
  </div>

  <div class="stat-row">
    <div class="stat-block">
      <div class="stat-value">Dec</div>
      <div class="stat-label">2023<br>Publication Date</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-block">
      <div class="stat-value gold">10</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Mandatory<br>Clauses (4–10)</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-block">
      <div class="stat-value violet">38</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Annex A<br>Controls</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-block">
      <div class="stat-value green">3yr</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Certification<br>Cycle</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-block">
      <div class="stat-value orange">~40%</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Control Overlap<br>with ISO 27001</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p class="prose">
    ISO/IEC 42001:2023 is the world's first certifiable international standard for Artificial Intelligence
    Management Systems (AIMS). Unlike sector-specific frameworks, it operates at the <strong>governance
    layer</strong> — defining how organisations establish policies, assess risks, govern lifecycles, and
    continuously improve their AI-related operations. For software companies in cryptographic security,
    this governance layer is the missing tier that neither FIPS 140-3, Common Criteria, nor ISO 27001 alone provides:
    <em>structured AI-specific risk management for the probabilistic components embedded within cryptographic infrastructure.</em>
  </p>

  <div class="callout">
    <div class="callout-label">⚡ Core Distinction</div>
    <p>ISO/IEC 42001 does <strong>not</strong> certify products or algorithms. It certifies that an
    organisation's <strong>management system</strong> for AI is established, operated, and continuously
    improved according to internationally recognised principles. For a cryptographic security firm,
    this means governing the AI components within your products — entropy validators, anomaly detectors,
    protocol negotiators, key lifecycle monitors — through an auditable, documented framework.</p>
  </div>

  <h3 style="font-family: var(--mono); font-size: 14px; color: var(--text-primary); margin: 32px 0 16px; letter-spacing: 0.04em;">WHO IN CRYPTOGRAPHIC SECURITY SHOULD IMPLEMENT ISO 42001?</h3>

  <div class="grid-3">
    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-accent"></div>
      <div class="card-label">Category A</div>
      <h3>PKI &amp; Certificate Infrastructure</h3>
      <p>Certificate Authorities, HSM vendors, key management service providers embedding ML anomaly detection or AI-driven certificate lifecycle automation.</p>
      <span class="tag">HIGH RELEVANCE</span>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-accent gold"></div>
      <div class="card-label">Category B</div>
      <h3>Cryptographic Library Developers</h3>
      <p>Open-source and commercial library maintainers (OpenSSL, BouncyCastle, libsodium vendors) adding AI-assisted side-channel detection or fuzzing intelligence.</p>
      <span class="tag" style="border-color: rgba(255,215,0,0.3); color: var(--accent-gold); background: rgba(255,215,0,0.08);">MEDIUM-HIGH</span>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-accent cyan"></div>
      <div class="card-label">Category C</div>
      <h3>Secure Communication Platforms</h3>
      <p>TLS/mTLS platforms, VPN vendors, and secure messaging providers using AI for traffic analysis, threat classification, or adaptive key rotation.</p>
      <span class="tag" style="border-color: rgba(0,255,204,0.3); color: var(--accent-cyan); background: rgba(0,255,204,0.08);">HIGH RELEVANCE</span>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-accent violet"></div>
      <div class="card-label">Category D</div>
      <h3>Post-Quantum Security Vendors</h3>
      <p>Companies developing, integrating, or commercialising ML-KEM, ML-DSA, SLH-DSA implementations — especially where AI governs migration decisions or entropy sourcing.</p>
      <span class="tag" style="border-color: rgba(167,139,250,0.3); color: var(--accent-violet); background: rgba(167,139,250,0.08);">CRITICAL</span>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-accent orange"></div>
      <div class="card-label">Category E</div>
      <h3>QRNG &amp; Quantum Entropy Providers</h3>
      <p>Quantum Random Number Generator vendors and entropy-as-a-service providers where AI validates entropy quality, detects degradation, or manages NIST SP 800-90B compliance.</p>
      <span class="tag" style="border-color: rgba(255,107,53,0.3); color: var(--accent-orange); background: rgba(255,107,53,0.08);">CRITICAL</span>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-accent green"></div>
      <div class="card-label">Category F</div>
      <h3>Crypto-Agility Orchestration</h3>
      <p>Policy engines and orchestration platforms that use AI/ML to manage algorithm deprecation timelines, automate cipher suite negotiation, or recommend migration paths.</p>
      <span class="tag" style="border-color: rgba(0,255,135,0.3); color: var(--accent-green); background: rgba(0,255,135,0.08);">CRITICAL</span>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- ─── SECTION 2: CRYPTOGRAPHIC SECURITY LAYER ─── -->
<section id="s2">
  <div class="section-header">
    <span class="section-num">02 //</span>
    <h2 class="section-title">ISO 42001 for <span class="highlight">Cryptographic Security</span> — The Governance Gap</h2>
  </div>

  <p class="prose">
    Classical cryptographic security frameworks (FIPS 140-3, Common Criteria, ISO 27001 Annex A.8.24)
    govern <strong>algorithms, key material, and information assets</strong>. They are deterministic-world
    standards: given defined inputs and approved algorithms, outputs are predictable and auditable.
    ISO 42001 addresses what happens when <strong>non-deterministic AI components</strong> are introduced
    into that deterministic cryptographic pipeline — a reality every modern cryptographic security
    company now faces.
  </p>

  <div class="callout gold">
    <div class="callout-label">⚙ The Core Problem</div>
    <p>Modern cryptographic infrastructure increasingly embeds AI at critical decision points: <strong>entropy
    quality scoring, anomaly detection on key usage patterns, adaptive certificate issuance policies,
    side-channel attack detection, and protocol negotiation optimisation.</strong> None of these AI components
    are governed by FIPS 140-3. None appear in ISO 27001's control set. ISO 42001 is the only
    internationally certifiable standard that addresses this gap.</p>
  </div>

  <h3 style="font-family: var(--mono); font-size: 13px; color: var(--text-primary); margin: 32px 0 16px; letter-spacing: 0.06em; text-transform: uppercase;">AI TOUCHPOINTS IN CRYPTOGRAPHIC SECURITY INFRASTRUCTURE</h3>

  <div class="grid-2">
    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-accent"></div>
      <div class="card-icon">🔑</div>
      <div class="card-label">Key Lifecycle Management</div>
      <h3>AI-Driven Key Rotation &amp; Revocation</h3>
      <p>ML models predict optimal rotation intervals based on usage telemetry. ISO 42001 Clause 8.2 requires documented risk assessment of the AI component itself — what happens if the model over-rotates or fails to flag compromised keys?</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-accent cyan"></div>
      <div class="card-icon">🎲</div>
      <div class="card-label">Entropy Validation</div>
      <h3>AI Entropy Quality Assessment</h3>
      <p>Statistical ML models validate TRNG and QRNG output quality against NIST SP 800-90B. ISO 42001's transparency requirements (Annex A.6.2) mandate explainable entropy rejection decisions — critical when a rejection halts a TLS handshake.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-accent violet"></div>
      <div class="card-icon">🔍</div>
      <div class="card-label">Threat Detection</div>
      <h3>Anomaly Detection on Cryptographic Operations</h3>
      <p>AI classifiers monitor for side-channel attack patterns, timing anomalies, and abnormal cipher suite negotiation. False positives can trigger outages; false negatives enable breaches. ISO 42001's performance monitoring (Clause 9.1) governs classifier accuracy requirements.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-accent gold"></div>
      <div class="card-icon">📜</div>
      <div class="card-label">Certificate Management</div>
      <h3>AI-Automated PKI Operations</h3>
      <p>Automated certificate issuance, validation, and revocation decisions made by AI agents operating as part of a CA. ISO 42001 Clause 8.4 (AI system impact assessment) applies directly — erroneous AI decisions affect digital trust infrastructure at scale.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-accent orange"></div>
      <div class="card-icon">🔄</div>
      <div class="card-label">Protocol Negotiation</div>
      <h3>Adaptive TLS/Cipher Suite Selection</h3>
      <p>AI-driven protocol negotiation selects cipher suites based on peer capability, threat context, and compliance requirements. Non-deterministic selection decisions require governance under ISO 42001 Clause 6.1.2 risk criteria.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-accent green"></div>
      <div class="card-icon">🏗</div>
      <div class="card-label">Supply Chain</div>
      <h3>Third-Party Cryptographic Component Governance</h3>
      <p>AI libraries sourced from third parties (hardware security modules, entropy services, cloud KMS providers) carry upstream AI risk. ISO 42001's supplier oversight controls (Annex A.10.6) provide the audit framework that neither FIPS 140-3 nor ISO 27001 fully addresses.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="callout violet">
    <div class="callout-label">🔗 Framework Synergy</div>
    <p>ISO 42001 is <strong>not a replacement</strong> for FIPS 140-3, ISO 27001, or Common Criteria. It is the
    <strong>AI governance overlay</strong> that sits above them. A cryptographic security company that holds FIPS 140-3
    validation and ISO 27001 certification but lacks ISO 42001 has certified its algorithms and its information
    security posture — but has left its AI components <strong>ungoverned by any certifiable standard.</strong></p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- ─── SECTION 3: CLAUSE ARCHITECTURE ─── -->
<section id="s3">
  <div class="section-header">
    <span class="section-num">03 //</span>
    <h2 class="section-title">Clause <span class="highlight">Architecture</span> — Applied to Cryptographic Security</h2>
  </div>

  <p class="prose" style="margin-bottom: 28px;">
    ISO 42001's mandatory clauses (4 through 10) follow the Harmonised Structure shared with ISO 27001
    and ISO 9001, enabling integrated management systems. Below is each clause mapped directly to
    its application in a cryptographic security software context.
  </p>

  <table class="clause-table">
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th style="width:90px">Clause</th>
        <th style="width:200px">Title</th>
        <th>Cryptographic Security Application</th>
        <th style="width:110px">Priority</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td class="clause-id">Cl. 4</td>
        <td><span class="clause-name">Organisational Context</span></td>
        <td>Define scope of AI components within cryptographic products: entropy validators, key rotation agents, anomaly detectors. Identify regulatory context: CNSA 2.0, NIS2, EU AI Act, FIPS mandates.</td>
        <td><span class="badge badge-blue">FOUNDATIONAL</span></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="clause-id">Cl. 5</td>
        <td><span class="clause-name">Leadership</span></td>
        <td>Establish AI Policy covering responsible use of probabilistic components in security-critical cryptographic operations. Assign AIMS ownership to CISO or Chief Cryptographer role.</td>
        <td><span class="badge badge-violet">GOVERNANCE</span></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="clause-id">Cl. 6.1</td>
        <td><span class="clause-name">Risk Planning</span></td>
        <td>Risk criteria must explicitly include quantum adversary threat models, non-deterministic AI behaviour in cryptographic decision paths, and algorithm deprecation scenarios. Dual assessment: AI risk (6.1.2) + AI system impact (6.1.4).</td>
        <td><span class="badge badge-red">CRITICAL</span></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="clause-id">Cl. 6.2</td>
        <td><span class="clause-name">AI Objectives</span></td>
        <td>Set measurable targets: entropy quality acceptance rate, anomaly detection F1-score thresholds, key rotation accuracy metrics. Link to PQC migration milestones (e.g., ML-KEM deployment by Q3 2026).</td>
        <td><span class="badge badge-blue">PLANNING</span></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="clause-id">Cl. 7</td>
        <td><span class="clause-name">Support</span></td>
        <td>Cryptographic AI competence requirements: staff must understand lattice-based cryptography, NIST PQC standards, and AI model behaviour in adversarial conditions. Document entropy of training data for ML-based classifiers.</td>
        <td><span class="badge badge-violet">ENABLEMENT</span></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="clause-id">Cl. 8.1</td>
        <td><span class="clause-name">Operational Control</span></td>
        <td>Operational governance of AI components in production cryptographic systems: inference pipeline controls, model versioning for deployed classifiers, secure model storage in HSM-adjacent environments.</td>
        <td><span class="badge badge-orange">OPERATIONAL</span></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="clause-id">Cl. 8.2</td>
        <td><span class="clause-name">AI Risk Assessment</span></td>
        <td><strong>Core operational clause.</strong> Ongoing risk assessment of deployed AI components: entropy scorer drift, classifier accuracy degradation under adversarial quantum inputs, model poisoning through compromised training pipelines. Reassess on every material model change.</td>
        <td><span class="badge badge-red">CRITICAL</span></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="clause-id">Cl. 8.3</td>
        <td><span class="clause-name">AI Risk Treatment</span></td>
        <td>Treatment plans for identified AI risks: human-in-the-loop overrides for high-stakes cryptographic decisions, fallback to deterministic algorithms when AI confidence falls below threshold, emergency cipher suite rollback procedures.</td>
        <td><span class="badge badge-red">CRITICAL</span></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="clause-id">Cl. 8.4</td>
        <td><span class="clause-name">AI System Impact Assessment</span></td>
        <td><strong>Unique to ISO 42001.</strong> Societal and systemic impact assessment of AI in cryptographic infrastructure: What is the blast radius if the AI anomaly detector generates a false positive at scale? How does AI-driven key revocation affect dependent supply chains?</td>
        <td><span class="badge badge-gold">HIGH</span></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="clause-id">Cl. 9</td>
        <td><span class="clause-name">Performance Evaluation</span></td>
        <td>KPIs for AI components in production: classifier drift monitoring, entropy validator accuracy against known-good samples, audit trail completeness for AI-assisted certificate decisions. Internal audit of AIMS against PQC migration objectives.</td>
        <td><span class="badge badge-blue">MONITORING</span></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="clause-id">Cl. 10</td>
        <td><span class="clause-name">Improvement</span></td>
        <td>Corrective action for AI failures: model retraining protocols post-incident, post-quantum algorithm adoption triggered by NIST deprecation notices, continuous improvement cycle aligned to PQC standards evolution (HQC expected FIPS ~2027).</td>
        <td><span class="badge badge-green">CONTINUOUS</span></td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

