<!-- ─── SECTION 5: RISK ASSESSMENT DEEP-DIVE ─── -->
<section id="s5">
  <div class="section-header">
    <span class="section-num">05 //</span>
    <h2 class="section-title">Risk Assessment <span class="highlight">Deep-Dive</span> — Non-Determinism in Quantum-Vulnerable Environments</h2>
  </div>

  <p class="prose">
    The most technically sophisticated question ISO 42001 must answer for PQC vendors is: <strong>how
    do you perform a risk assessment on a component whose outputs are inherently non-deterministic,
    operating in an environment threatened by adversaries with exponentially growing computational
    capabilities?</strong> The standard's architecture provides a structural answer, even if it
    does not use the words "non-deterministic" or "quantum" in its normative text.
  </p>

  <div class="callout violet">
    <div class="callout-label">📐 Structural Mechanism</div>
    <p>ISO 42001 handles non-determinism by <strong>separating risk assessment from impact assessment</strong>
    (Clauses 6.1.2 vs 6.1.4), requiring ongoing operational re-assessment (Clause 8.2), and mandating
    treatment plans with dynamic update triggers (Clause 8.3). Together, these create a governance loop
    that <em>institutionalises the management of variance</em>, rather than assuming deterministic outputs.
    This is structurally identical to what cryptographic agility management requires.</p>
  </div>

  <h3 style="font-family: var(--mono); font-size: 13px; color: var(--text-primary); margin: 32px 0 20px; letter-spacing: 0.06em; text-transform: uppercase;">THE DUAL ASSESSMENT ARCHITECTURE</h3>

  <div class="grid-2">
    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-accent"></div>
      <div class="card-label">Clause 6.1.2 + 8.2</div>
      <h3>AI Risk Assessment</h3>
      <p>Evaluates <strong>probability and severity</strong> of adverse AI behaviour. For non-deterministic systems, practitioners cannot assign fixed probabilities — instead, ISO 42001 requires defining <em>risk criteria</em> against which a <em>distribution of outcomes</em> is evaluated.</p>
      <p style="margin-top: 10px; font-size: 12px; color: var(--text-muted);">For PQC vendors: assess the probability distribution of entropy validator false rejections, anomaly detector false positives under quantum-adversarial inputs, and migration advisor recommendation errors.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-accent gold"></div>
      <div class="card-label">Clause 6.1.4 + 8.4</div>
      <h3>AI System Impact Assessment</h3>
      <p>Evaluates <strong>consequences</strong> at socio-technical scale: intended use, foreseeable misuse, impacts on individuals, groups, and society. Unique to ISO 42001 — no equivalent exists in ISO 27001 or FIPS 140-3.</p>
      <p style="margin-top: 10px; font-size: 12px; color: var(--text-muted);">For PQC vendors: what is the blast radius if the AI-driven certificate authority makes erroneous revocation decisions at scale? How does a flawed entropy validator affect dependent PKI hierarchies?</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3 style="font-family: var(--mono); font-size: 13px; color: var(--text-primary); margin: 32px 0 20px; letter-spacing: 0.06em; text-transform: uppercase;">STRIDE THREAT MODEL — APPLIED TO AI-IN-CRYPTOGRAPHIC-INFRASTRUCTURE</h3>

  <table class="clause-table">
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>STRIDE Threat</th>
        <th>ISO 42001 Lifecycle Stage</th>
        <th>Cryptographic / PQC Context</th>
        <th>Annex A Reference</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><span class="badge badge-blue">SPOOFING</span></td>
        <td>Inception (design)</td>
        <td>Adversarial inputs masquerading as legitimate entropy samples to poison QRNG validation models</td>
        <td>A.8.1</td>
      </tr>
